localizedDescriptions.en: Document to communicate information to others, commonly in response to a request from another party.
Identification information about the report.
The status of the entire report. Note: This is not the status of any of the report components.
The result, including findings and the laboratory's interpretation, of an investigation performed on specimens collected from an individual or related to that individual.
Name of the laboratory investigation performed on the specimen(s).

annotations.comment: A test result may be for a single analyte, or a group of items, including panel tests. It is strongly recommended that 'Test name' be coded with a terminology, for example LOINC or SNOMED CT. For example: 'Glucose', 'Urea and Electrolytes', 'Swab', 'Cortisol (am)', 'Potassium in perspiration' or 'Melanoma histopathology'. The name may sometimes include specimen type and patient state, for example 'Fasting blood glucose' or include other information, as 'Potassium (PNA blood gas)'.

localizedDescriptions.en: A physical sample collected from, or related to, an individual for the purpose of investigation, examination or analysis.

annotations.comment: For example: Tissue or body fluid.

localizedDescriptions.en: The type of specimen.

annotations.comment: For example: Venous blood, bacterial culture, cytology, or tissue sample. Coding of the specimen type with a terminology is preferred, where possible.

localizedDescriptions.en: A unique identifier of the specimen, normally assigned by the laboratory.

annotations.comment: Sometimes called the Accession Identifier. Specimen containers, for example vacuum vials or tissue cassettes, have their own identitiers which may be recorded in the 'Container identifier' element in the 'Specimen container' archetype.

localizedDescriptions.en: The date and time that the sample was received at the laboratory.
The date and time that collection has been ordered to take place or has taken place.

annotations.comment: This datetime will be captured primarily in the INSTRUCTION timing, ACTION time or OBSERVATION times. However, as this is a critical piece of information, it can be useful to also associate it directly with the specimen itself.

localizedDescriptions.en: Unique identifier of the parent specimen, where the specimen is split into sub-samples.

annotations.comment: For example: A specific histology slide specimen can have a specific paraffin wax block as its parent specimen.

localizedDescriptions.en: Additional narrative about the specimen not captured in other fields.
The status of the laboratory test result as a whole.

annotations.comment:
The values have been specifically chosen to match those in the HL7 FHIR Diagnostic report, historically derived from HL7v2 practice. Other local codes/terms can be used via the Text 'choice'.

This element is multiple occurrence to cater for the use cases where statuses for different aspects of the result have been split into several elements.

localizedDescriptions.en: The existence of the test is registered in the Laboratory Information System, but there is nothing yet available.
This is a partial (e.g. initial, interim or preliminary) Test Result: data in the Test Result may be incomplete or unverified.
Verified early results are available, but not all results are final. This is a sub-category of 'Partial'.
The Test result is complete and verified by an authorised person.
The result has been modified subsequent to being Final, and is complete and verified by the responsible pathologist, and result data has been changed.
The result has been modified subsequent to being Final, and is complete and verified by the responsible pathologist. This is a sub-category of 'Amended'.
Subsequent to being final, the report has been modified by adding new content. The existing content is unchanged. This is a sub-category of 'Amended'.
The result is unavailable because the test was not started or not completed (also sometimes called 'aborted').
The Test Result has been withdrawn following previous Final release.
The date and/or time that ‘Overall test status’ was issued.
The diagnostic service or discipline that is responsible for the laboratory test result.

annotations.comment: This is intended to be a general categorisation and not to capture the organisational name of the laboratory. For example: anatomical pathology, immunology and transfusion medicine, medical microbiology, clinical pharmacology, medical genetics, medical biochemistry. Alternatively more granular sub categories or sub disciplines, such as endocrinology, haematology, and allergology services, may be used. This may assist clinicians in filtering between categories of results. Coding with a terminology is desirable, where possible.

localizedDescriptions.en: Description of clinical information available at the time of interpretation of results.

annotations.comment: This data element may include a link to the original clinical information provided in the test request.

localizedDescriptions.en: Cluster to combine sequencing assay, General sequencing parameters and all variant results of a single analysis.
A local identifier that is assigned by the receiving laboratory information system (LIS) in order to track the test process.
General sequencing result parameter.
Normal vs. tumor sample.
Identifies germline mutations.
Identifies somatic mutations.
Tumor cell content determinded by pathologic/histologic methods.
Tumor cell content determinded by bioinformatic methods.
Microsatellite instability (MSI).
Tumor Mutational Burden (TMB) per Megabase.
BRCAness is defined as a phenotypic copy of germline BRCA mutations.
To record details of the sequencing analysis including a list of all tested genes if panel sequencing was performed.
Name of the technology used for sequencing analysis.

annotations.comment:
WGS - Whole Genome Sequencing
WES - Whole Exome Sequencing 
Panel based sequencing
Metagenomic sequencing
RNA sequencing

localizedDescriptions.en: An instrument, apparatus, implant, material or similar, used in the provision of healthcare. In this context, a medical device includes a broad range of devices which act through a variety of physical, mechanical, thermal or similar means but specifically excludes devices which act through medicinal means such as pharmacological, metabolic or immunological methods.  The scope is inclusive of disposable devices as well as durable or persisting devices that require tracking, maintenance activities or regular calibration, recognising that each type of device has specific data recording requirements.
Identification of the medical device, preferably by a common name, a formal fully descriptive name or, if required, by class or category of device.

annotations.comment: This data element will capture the term, phrase or category used in clinical practice. For example: <brand name><machine> (XYZ Audiometer); <size> <brand name> <intravenous catheter> (14G Jelco IV catheter); or <brand name/type> <implant>. Coding with a terminology is desirable, where possible, although this may be local and depending on local supplies available.

localizedDescriptions.en: Name of manufacturer.
The exact number assigned by the manufacturer, as it appears in the manufacturer's catalogue, device labeling, or accompanying packaging.
Identification of the version of software being used in the medical device.

annotations.comment: When the medical device is an actual software application, record the version of the software using this data element. When the medical device has multiple software applications embedded within it, record each software component in a separate CLUSTER archetype within the Components SLOT - either as a nested instance of another CLUSTER.device archetype or using a CLUSTER archetype designed specifically for recording software details (but not yet available at time of this archetype development).

localizedDescriptions.en: Additional narrative about the device not captured in other fields.
Name of the kit used for the experiment.
Type of nucleic acid used for sequencing, e.g. DNA, RNA oder cf-DNA.
List of all tested genes, if panel sequencing was performed.
The official gene symbol approved by the HGNC, which is a short abbreviated form of the gene name.
The full gene name approved by the HGNC that convey the character or function of the gene.
List of all tested regions, if panel sequencing was performed.
Chromosomal location of tested region.
Start position of the tested region.
End position of the tested region.
Findings and annotations related to one variant found in a human individual by a sequencing test.
A sequence file that is used as a reference to describe genetic variants that are present in an analysed sequence.
The reference genome assembled as a representative model of the human genome.
The name of the data source containing the reference sequence.
Network address.
A citation of a digital resource used as an source of authoritative or expert information, and/or to items contained within the resource.

annotations.comment: For example: a genomics pipeline history, a database of genomic variants, or a database of healthcare procedure guidelines.

localizedDescriptions.en: The name of the knowledge base.

annotations.comment: For example: Galaxy/Snakemake; dbSNP; or CADD.

localizedDescriptions.en: The name of the referenced item within the knowledge base.

annotations.comment: For example: rs139581412.

localizedDescriptions.en: The version of the referenced item within the knowledge base.
Description of the variation at the genomic level following the HGVS nomenclature.

annotations.comment:
For example: 'g.33038255C>A'.

If both this element and the 'Structured variant' SLOT are used simultaneously, they need to represent identical data.

localizedDescriptions.en: A human genetic sequence change where, compared to a genomic reference sequence, a DNA segment, usually larger than 1 kilobase (kb), was deleted or duplicated.
Position or range of possible positions of the first nucleotide of the CNV.
Position or range of possible positions of the first nucleotide of the CNV.
Position or range of possible positions of the first nucleotide of the CNV.
Position or range of possible positions of the last nucleotide of the CNV.
Position or range of possible positions of the last nucleotide of the CNV.
Position or range of possible positions of the last nucleotide of the CNV.
Number of appearance of the allele.
Type of sequence alteration.

annotations.comment: Different types of impact, such as low-level amplification or whole gene deletion, should be recorded using the 'Functional impact' Cluster within the CLUSTER.genomic_variant_result archetype.

localizedDescriptions.en: A sequence alteration whereby the copy number of a given region is greater than the reference sequence.
A sequence alteration whereby the copy number of a given region is less than the reference sequence.
A human genetic sequence change where, compared to a genomic reference sequence, a range of nucleotides are replaced by a sequence from elsewhere in the genome.
The position of the first nucleotide of the converted range.
The position of the last nucleotide of the converted range.
The position of the first nucleotide of the replacing sequence.
The position of the last nucleotide of the replacing sequence.
A human genetic sequence change where, compared to a genomic reference sequence, one or more nucleotides are not present (deleted).

annotations.comment: For example: changing 'AGAAtCACA' to 'AGAA_CACA'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Position of the deleted nucleotide or the first nucleotide of the deleted range.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence  'AGAatcACA' is changed to 'AGA___ACA' the start position is 4.

localizedDescriptions.en: Position of the last nucleotide of the deleted range.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence  'AGAatcACA' is changed to 'AGA___ACA' the end position is 6.

localizedDescriptions.en: The deleted nucleotide or sequence.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence  'AGAatcACA' is changed to 'AGA___ACA' the deleted sequence is 'ATC'.

localizedDescriptions.en: A human genetic sequence change where, compared to a genomic reference sequence, one or more nucleotides are replaced by one or more other nucleotides and which is not a substitution, inversion or conversion.

annotations.comment: For example: changing 'AGGCtcaTT' to 'AGGCcTT'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Position of the deleted nucleotide or the first nucleotide of the deleted range.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGGCtcaTT' is changed to 'AGGCcTT', the start position is 5.

localizedDescriptions.en: Position of the last nucleotide of the deleted range.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGGCtcaTT' is changed to 'AGGCcTT', the end position is 7.

localizedDescriptions.en: The deleted nucleotide or sequence.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGGCtcaTT' is changed to 'AGGCcTT', the deleted sequence is 'TCA'.

localizedDescriptions.en: The inserted nucleotide or sequence.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGGCtcaTT' is changed to 'AGGCcTT', the inserted nucleotide is 'C'.

localizedDescriptions.en: A human genetic sequence change where, compared to a genomic reference sequence, a copy of one or more nucleotides are inserted directly 3' of the original copy of that sequence.

annotations.comment: For example: changing 'AGtagaGG' to 'AGtagatagaGG'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Position of the duplicated nucleotide or the first nucleotide of the duplicated range.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGtagaGG' is changed to 'AGtagatagaGG', the start position is 3.

localizedDescriptions.en: Position of the last nucleotide of the duplicated range.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGtagaGG' is changed to 'AGtagatagaGG', the end position is 6.

localizedDescriptions.en: The duplicated nucleotide or sequence.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGtagaGG' is changed to 'AGtagatagaGG', the duplicated sequence is 'TAGA'.

localizedDescriptions.en: A human genetic sequence change where, compared to the genomic reference sequence, one or more nucleotides are inserted and where the insertion is not a copy of a sequence immediately 5'.

annotations.comment: For example: changing 'AGTAGAGG' to 'AGTAGatAGG'.

localizedDescriptions.en: The position of the first of the two flanking nucleotides.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGTAGAGG' is changed to 'AGTAGatAGG', the start position is 5.

localizedDescriptions.en: The position of the last of the two flanking nucleotides.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGTAGAGG' is changed to 'AGTAGatAGG', the end position is 6.

localizedDescriptions.en: The inserted nucleotide or sequence.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGTAGAGG' is changed to 'AGTAGatAGG', the inserted sequence is 'AT'.

localizedDescriptions.en: A human genetic sequence change where more than one nucleotide replaces the original sequence with the reverse complement of the original sequence, compared to a genomic reference sequence.

annotations.comment: For example: changing 'TCAG' to 'CTGA'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Position of the first nucleotide of the inverted range.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'CAtcagCCT' is changed to 'CActgaCCT', the start position is 3.

localizedDescriptions.en: Position of the last nucleotide of the inverted range.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'CAtcagCCT' is changed to 'CActgaCCT', the end position is 6.

localizedDescriptions.en: The inverted sequence.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'CAtcagCCT' is changed to 'CActgaCCT', the inverted sequence is 'TCAG'.

localizedDescriptions.en: A human genetic sequence change where, compared to a genomic reference sequence, a segment of one or more nucleotides (the repeat unit) is present several times, one after the other.

annotations.comment: For example: changing 'CACGGCCT' to 'CACGGcggcggCCT'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Position of the first nucleotide of the repeated range.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'CACGGCCT' is changed to 'CACGGcggcggCCT', the start position is 3.

localizedDescriptions.en: Position of the last nucleotide of the repeated range.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'CACGGCCT' is changed to 'CACGGcggcggCCT', the end position is 5.

localizedDescriptions.en: A repeated unit consisting of a repeated sequence and a copy number.

annotations.comment: This cluster is repeatable to allow for mixed repeats. For example: for a variant where the reference sequence is 'GGC[9]GGA[1]GGC[10]', a mixed repeat could be 'GGC[10]GGA[1]GGC[9]GGA[1]GGC[10]'. The numbers in brackets in the example are the copy numbers.

localizedDescriptions.en: The intended position of this repeat unit within the overall sequence of repeat units.

annotations.comment:
This element is only relevant for mixed repeats.

For example: for a variant where the reference sequence is 'GGC[9]GGA[1]GGC[10]' and the mixed repeat is 'GGC[10]GGA[1]GGC[9]GGA[2]GGC[11]', the 'Repeat order' for 'GGC[10]' is 1, for 'GGA[1]' 2, for 'GGC[9]' 3, and so on.

localizedDescriptions.en: The sequence of nucleotides that has been repeated.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'CACGGCCT' is changed to 'CACGGcggcggCT', the repeated sequence is 'CGG'.

localizedDescriptions.en: The total number of times the 'Repeated sequence' was repeated.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'CACGGCCT' is changed to 'CACGGcggcggCCT', the copy number is 3.

localizedDescriptions.en: A human genetic sequence change where, compared to a genomic reference sequence, one nucleotide is replaced by one other nucleotide.

annotations.comment: For example: changing 'AGTAgAGG' to 'AGTAtAGG'.

localizedDescriptions.en: The position of the substituted nucleotide.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGTAgAGG' is changed to 'AGTAtAGG', the position substituted is 5.

localizedDescriptions.en: The nucleotide at reference position.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGTAgAGG' is changed to 'AGTAtAGG', the reference nucleotide is 'G'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Substituted nucleotide.

annotations.comment: For example: for a variant where the reference sequence 'AGTAgAGG' is changed to 'AGTAtAGG', the new nucleotide is 'T'.

localizedDescriptions.en: A sequence change where, compared to a reference sequence, a one or more nucleotides are changed.
Chromosome identifier.
Chromosome 1.
Chromosome 2.
Chromosome 3.
Chromosome 4.
Chromosome 5.
Chromosome 6.
Chromosome 7.
Chromosome 8.
Chromosome 9.
Chromosome 10.
Chromosome 11.
Chromosome 12.
Chromosome 13.
Chromosome 14.
Chromosome 15.
Chromosome 16.
Chromosome 17.
Chromosome 18.
Chromosome 19.
Chromosome 20.
Chromosome 21.
Chromosome 22.
Chromosome X.
Chromosome Y.
The position of the first nucleotide of the changed range for a simple variant. ("Start" in vcf-file).
The position of the last nucleotide of the changed range for a simple variant. ("End" in vcf-file).
The observed alternate nucleotide or nucleotide sequence ("Alt" in vcf-file).
The reference nucleotide or nucleotide sequence. ("Ref" in vcf-file).
Translocation variant.
Position of first breakpoint relative to start of "Chromosome 1".

A value of "+" indicates that the chromosomal segment at the second breakpoint is connected to the chromosomal segment at the first breakpoint right of "Breakpoint position 1". A value of "-" indicates that the chromosomal segment at the second breakpoint is connected to the chromosomal segment of the first breakpoint left of "Breakpoint position 1".
Position of second breakpoint relative to start of "Chromosome 2".

A value of "+" indicates that the chromosomal segment at the first breakpoint is connected to the chromosomal segment at the second breakpoint right of "Breakpoint position 2". A value of "-" indicates that the chromosomal segment at the first breakpoint is connected to the chromosomal segment of the second breakpoint left of "Breakpoint position 2".
The description of the variant using the recommendations of the accepted HGVS nomeclature named extension ISCN.
Structured details about the transcript which is potentially affected by the variant.
A sequence file that is used as a reference to describe genetic variants that are present in an analysed sequence.
The reference genome assembled as a representative model of the human genome.
The name of the data source containing the reference sequence.
A unique identifier to refer to a sequence record in a sequence repository.
Network address.
The human readable name for the region of interest.

annotations.comment: For example: 'exon number', 'intron number', 'splice site' or other.

localizedDescriptions.en: Distance in nucleotides between mutation and exon–intron junction.
Description of the variation at the DNA level following the HGVS nomenclature.

annotations.comment: For example: 'c.5249C>T'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Description of the variation at the protein level following the HGVS nomenclature.

annotations.comment: For example: 'p.T1750M'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Codified type for associated amino acid marker.
The sequence at a given position is identical to the reference sequence.
A deletion in the amino acid sequence.
A duplication in the amino acid sequence.
A frameshift in the amino acid sequence.
A variant in a sequence affecting the translation initiation codon.
An insertion in the amino acid sequence.
An insertion/deletion in the amino acid sequence.
One amino acid is replaced by another amino acid.
An amino acid is replaced by a translational stop codon (termination codon).
A variant in a DNA sequence that does not change the amino acid sequence of the encoded protein.
A variant in a sequence affecting the translational stop codon.
Description of the variation at the RNA level following the HGVS nomenclature.

annotations.comment: For example: 'r.76a>u'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Estimate of the effects that the variant may have on the transcript.
The calculated value.

annotations.comment: For example: '30.2'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Human readable version of the predicted impact.

annotations.comment: For example: 'probably damaging'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Interpretation of the variation linked to a specific paper.
Single word or phrase describing the reported impact of the specific variant.

annotations.comment: For example: 'activating', 'deactivating', 'dysfunction', 'gain of function'. Coding with a terminology is preferred, where possible.

localizedDescriptions.en: Reference to information held elsewhere, in the same EHR or external to the EHR.
Description about the citation.
Representation of the citation.
Representation of the citation.
Representation of the citation.
Link to the original data.
Comment about the citation.
Structured details about the gene carrying the variant.
The official gene symbol approved by the HGNC, which is a short abbreviated form of the gene name.

annotations.comment: For example 'CHD5'.

localizedDescriptions.en: The full gene name approved by the HGNC that conveys the character or function of the gene.

annotations.comment: For example 'Chromodomain helicase DNA binding protein 5'.

localizedDescriptions.en: The fraction of gene region covered by copy number.
States if the gene is part of a fusion gene and if it is the first or second part of the fusion gene.
First part of a fusion gene.
Second part of a fusion gene.
The clinical significance according to the ACMG recommendations.
Pathogenic variant.
Likely pathogenic variant.
Variant of uncertain significance.
Likely benign variant.
Benign variant.
The number of the exon which is part of the fusion.
The ID of the transcript with the highest predicted impact.

annotations.comment: For example: 'ENST00000413998.7'.

localizedDescriptions.en: The total number of reads mapped at this specific location.
The number of reads that support the reported variant.
The relative frequency of an allele at a particular locus.

annotations.comment: For example: '0.63'.

localizedDescriptions.en: The relative frequency of a particular allele in the population.
The population allele frequency.

annotations.comment: For example: '0.43'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Structured details about the quality filters that have been applied to the data.

annotations.comment: This field is derived from the FILTER column of VCF.

localizedDescriptions.en: Name of the quality filter.

annotations.comment: For example: 'q10'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Quality filter extended description.

annotations.comment: For example: 'at this site the quality is below 10'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Did the variant pass the quality filter?

annotations.comment: Record as 'True' if the filter was passed.

localizedDescriptions.en: The ratio of the strand bias.
The Phred-scaled p-value of the strand bias.
Genotype encoded as allele values.

annotations.comment: The format for the genotype should be value separated by either of / or | (0 for the reference allele, 1 for the first alternate, etc.). For example: '1 | 0' or '0/0/1'.

localizedDescriptions.en: The level of occurrence of a single DNA marker within a set of chromosomes.

annotations.comment: This is the human readable version of genotype, e.g.: 'Heterozygous', 'Homozygous'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Heteroplasmic.
Homoplasmic.
Homozygous.
Heterozygous.
Hemizygous.
Conditional genotype quality, encoded as a Phred quality.
A comma separated list of the log10-scaled genotype likelihoods for all possible genotypes, given the reference and the alternate alleles.
MTBP Classification
Reference to information held elsewhere, in the same EHR or external to the EHR.
Description about the citation.
Representation of the citation.
Representation of the citation.
Representation of the citation.
Link to the original data.
Comment about the citation.
Narrative description of the key findings.

annotations.comment: For example: 'Pattern suggests significant renal impairment'. The content of the conclusion will vary, depending on the investigation performed. This conclusion should be aligned with the coded 'Test diagnosis'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Single word, phrase or brief description that represents the clinical meaning and significance of the laboratory test result.

annotations.comment: For example: 'Severe hepatic impairment', 'Salmonella contamination'. Coding of the diagnosis with a terminology is strongly recommended, where possible. This diagnosis should be aligned with the narrative in the 'Conclusion'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Additional narrative about the test result not captured in other fields.
A local identifier assigned by the receiving Laboratory Information System (LIS) to track the test process.

annotations.comment: This identifier is an internal tracking number assigned by the LIS, and it not intended to be the name of the test.

localizedDescriptions.en: Details about the test request.

annotations.comment:
In most situations there is one test request and a single corresponding test result, however this repeating cluster allows for the situation where there may be multiple test requests reported using a single test result.

As an example: 'a clinician asks for blood glucose in one request and Urea/electrolytes in a second request, but the lab analyser does both and the lab wishes to report these together'.

localizedDescriptions.en: Name of the original laboratory test requested.

annotations.comment: This data element is to be used when the test requested differs from the test actually performed by the laboratory.

localizedDescriptions.en: The local identifier assigned by the requesting clinical system.

annotations.comment: Equivalent to the HL7 Placer Order Identifier.

localizedDescriptions.en: The local identifier assigned to the test order by the order filler, usually by the Laboratory Information System (LIS).

annotations.comment: Assigning an identifier to a request by the Laboratory lnformation System (LIS) enables tracking progress of the request and enables linking results to requests. It also provides a reference to assist with enquiries and it is usually equivalent to the HL7 Filler Order Identifier.
